[{"sha":"e13f2524711c39972febb784398a8f8038a63c30","author":{"name":"rsun","email":"e07b22d99c92b805a489a0254d7957fd2fada7fd@bdti.com"},"message":"Port micro op GATHER_ND and its test code from lite","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/e13f2524711c39972febb784398a8f8038a63c30"},{"sha":"4a9266d05ae7d6f64385988d1e3f130277f21791","author":{"name":"rsun","email":"e07b22d99c92b805a489a0254d7957fd2fada7fd@bdti.com"},"message":"Correct incorrect output dims in micro gather_nd_test.cc","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Intel-tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/4a9266d05ae7d6f64385988d1e3f130277f21791"},{"sha":"8a9f8e2fa7460a2063ef068110858c3d84cf1a99","author":{"name":"Edward Loper","email":"4e70de59cddd527517e9ce09eb7412beeffcbd1a@google.com"},"message":"tf.Struct: Add `AnonymousStruct` class, which is a fallback used to decode `tf.Struct` values when the original type is unavailable.

Also add `reinterpret_struct`, which can be used to convert a struct value to a new Struct type as long as the field values are type-compatible.  (The primary use-case intended for `reinterpret_struct` is converting to/from anonymous structs; this shouldn't usually be necessary, but might be helpful in a few circumstances.)

Note: In a future change, we will be splitting the `Struct` type into two separate but related types: `Struct` and `ExtensionType`, where:

* Struct is basically a map<str, value>, and does support subclassing,
  adding new, properties, methods, etc.

* ExtensionType is a user-defined class, with support for adding new
  properties, methods, etc., and for registering dispatchers.

* The state of an ExtensionType can be stored using a Struct.

* Comparing this to Python, `ExtensionType` is like a class, and `Struct`
  is like the `__dict__` for an instance of a class.

[{"sha":"6dce1e85f873b7f320ec41714d6df8e1b974b2ea","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Add legalization for BatchMatMulV3 op

BatchMatMulV3 differs from BatchMatMulV2 that it also takes "Tout" as an attribute to support mixed precision generating output of a different type.

Added tf2xla BatchMatMulV3 kernel and using that from MLIR fallback. This is because of a missing optimization in BatchMatMulV2 native legalization. Updated the corresponding TODO.

Also, generate MLIR definition for the BatchMatMulV3 op.

[{"sha":"a303a03f2f07a8e4937e876139ca61c1b433cc06","author":{"name":"Chad Bailey","email":"45db7ff864ef6ef24d410b7457d05515521178db@gmail.com"},"message":"Added clarity: remote-exec connection requirement

This is a secondary change to PR #28578 

Details:
According to the [Provisioner Connection](https://www.terraform.io/docs/language/resources/provisioners/connection.html) page, provisioners require the connection block.

This change of behavior is shown prominently within a note on the [Provisioner Connection](https://www.terraform.io/docs/language/resources/provisioners/connection.html) page:

> Note: In Terraform 0.11 and earlier, providers could set default values for some connection settings, so that connection blocks could sometimes be omitted. This feature was removed in 0.12 in order to make Terraform's behavior more predictable.

However, this behavioral change is omitted from the [remote-exec provisioner](https://www.terraform.io/docs/language/resources/provisioners/remote-exec.html) page which is where a user will be if they are attempting to follow the prior behavior when this was permissible in versions prior to 0.12. We typecheck the reconciler against each one of our host configs.
`yarn flow dom` checks it against the DOM renderer, `yarn flow native`
checks it against the native renderer, and so on.

To do this, we generate separate flowconfig files.

Currently, there is no root-level host config, so running Flow
directly via `flow` CLI doesn't work. You have to use the `yarn flow`
command and pick a specific renderer.

A drawback of this design, though, is that our Flow setup doesn't work
with other tooling. Namely, editor integrations.

I think the intent of this was maybe so you don't run Flow against a
renderer than you intended, see it pass, and wrongly think you fixed
all the errors. However, since they all run in CI, I don't think this
is a big deal. In practice, I nearly always run Flow against the same
renderer (DOM), and I'm guessing that's the most common workflow for
others, too.

So what I've done in this commit is modify the `yarn flow` command to
copy the generated `.flowconfig` file into the root directory. The
editor integration will pick this up and show Flow information for
whatever was the last renderer you checked.

Everything else about the setup is the same, and all the renderers will

Change-Id: I575ee701b2ad431c32f518b70baa738b864ceb63","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GulajavaMinistudio/tensorflow/commits/6f92d219237a3b6a2fb3120e7609dea67dd6b8fd"},{"sha":"92152f1624501ba3c44cc2a71fb226c8004db259","author":{"name":"Yunxing Dai","email":"0e6edd405794f4fb8b1584e93c0a178f5c32bc6a@google.com"},"message":"Implement argument forwarding in value_inference

This cl allows us recursively peek outside of current control flow function and forward arguments inside into controlflow.  E.g.,:
```
 pred = .. dynamic value..

 op = 1
 if (pred) {
   if (pred) {
     return op
   } else {
     return op
   }
  } else {
    if (pred) {
      return op
    } else {
      return op
    }
  }
```

We are now able to tell the value of the nest conditional comes from the constant outside of the conditional.

Change-Id: Ic185201e40b69f47ec1ba8a1ab93595e4dc6d01d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/GulajavaMinistudio/tensorflow/commits/92152f1624501ba3c44cc2a71fb226c8004db259"},{"sha":"8a9f8e2fa7460a2063ef068110858c3d84cf1a99","author":{"name":"Edward Loper","email":"4e70de59cddd527517e9ce09eb7412beeffcbd1a@google.com"},"message":"tf.Struct: Add `AnonymousStruct` class, which is a fallback used to decode `tf.Struct` values when the original type is unavailable.

Also add `reinterpret_struct`, which can be used to convert a struct value to a new Struct type as long as the field values are type-compatible.  (The primary use-case intended for `reinterpret_struct` is converting to/from anonymous structs; this shouldn't usually be necessary, but might be helpful in a few circumstances.)

Note: In a future change, we will be splitting the `Struct` type into two separate but related types: `Struct` and `ExtensionType`, where:

* Struct is basically a map<str, value>, and does support subclassing,
  adding new, properties, methods, etc.

* ExtensionType is a user-defined class, with support for adding new
  properties, methods, etc., and for registering dispatchers.

* The state of an ExtensionType can be stored using a Struct.

* Comparing this to Python, `ExtensionType` is like a class, and `Struct`
  is like the `__dict__` for an instance of a class.

In this case, Copy won't read more data from a "last_written"
container than required, while feeding the desynchronized path.

Sometimes Copy don't get fused into an island and behaves
